                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Shades are generated by adjusting the lightness value in HSL color space. Starting from your chosen color, the tool creates a range from very dark (near black) to very light (near white) by incrementally changing the lightness percentage while keeping hue and saturation constant.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the difference between a shade and a tint?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>A shade is created by adding black to a color (decreasing lightness). A tint is created by adding white (increasing lightness). A tone is created by adding gray. In common usage, 'shades' often refers to the full range from dark to light.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I use these shades in my CSS?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Copy the HEX or HSL values and define them as CSS custom properties (variables): --color-100 through --color-900. This follows the Tailwind CSS convention where 100 is lightest and 900 is darkest. Then use var(--color-500) etc. throughout your stylesheet.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How many shades should I generate for a design system?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>A typical design system uses 9-11 shades per color (e.g., 50, 100, 200, 300, 400, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900, 950). This gives enough variation for backgrounds, borders, text, and interactive states without being overwhelming.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I generate shades for multiple colors?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Generate shades for each of your brand colors separately and combine them into your design system. Most design systems have a primary color, a neutral/gray scale, and 2-3 semantic colors (success green, error red, warning yellow).</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>

